          <source>Check your knowledge</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>Which statement best describes the information in a device template?</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>The hardware specification of a device connected to your application.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>Hardware details are not captured by a device template.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>The data and commands a device can exchange with your application.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>The template is a specification that captures all the potential information and commands that can be exchanged between your code and the physical device.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>The over-the-wire protocol used to communicate with a device.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="111" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>The communication protocol is not part of a device template.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="112" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>True or false: you must have a physical device to test your IoT Central application.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="113" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>True</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="114" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>You can use simulated devices for testing.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="115" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>False</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="116" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>IoT Central automatically creates a simulated device for you when you create a device template.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="117" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>You can also code custom software simulations.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="118" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>These options let you thoroughly test your application before connecting a physical device.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="119" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>Suppose you have five physical devices communicating with IoT Central.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="120" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>How many connection strings would you have?</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="121" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>One: the connection string is shared by all connected devices.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="122" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>Shared connection strings would not allow IoT Central to uniquely identify each device.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="123" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>Two: one in active use and one backup in case the primary is compromised.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="124" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>Shared connection strings would not allow IoT Central to uniquely identify each device.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="125" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>Five: every device needs a unique connection string.</source>
        </trans-unit><trans-unit id="126" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve" uid="learn.monitor-manage-device-with-iotcentral.6-knowledge-check">
          <source>The connection string identifies the device to IoT Central, so each device needs its own.</source>
